messages.content:
By 1920, the Ugaritic Empire had significantly diminished in size and power, retaining control over only a few territories in the Middle East and North Africa. Its borders and territories at that time were as follows:

- Northern border: The southern regions of modern-day Turkey;
- Southern border: The northern regions of modern-day Sudan along the Nile River;
- Eastern border: The western regions of modern-day Iran;
- Western border: The eastern portions of modern-day Libya, as well as the coastlines of modern-day Israel, Lebanon, and parts of Egypt.

In 1920, the capital of the Ugaritic Empire had shifted back to Ugarit, its original and symbolic center. However, due to the evolution of the Ugaritic language over time, the name of the capital city changed. Assuming the development of the Ugaritic language throughout history, the capital city in 1920 might have been called "Ugaretan" – a linguistic derivative of the original name "Ugarit."
